'''Architecture studio''' is a class in an [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate]] or [[Postgraduate education|graduate]] [[Professional degree|professional]] [[architecture]] program (such as a [[Bachelor of Architecture]] or [[Master of Architecture]] program) in which students receive hands-on instruction in [[architectural design]].  Typically, architecture studio classes include distinctive educational techniques, such as "desk crits" (project critiques delivered at a student's desk) and "juries", meetings of the students with more than one tutors around the production of students for a multi-layered open discussion where all students are supposed to participate.<ref>Dinham, Sarah M.  [http://www.eric.ed.gov:80/ERICWebPortal/custom/portlets/recordDetails/detailmini.jsp?_nfpb=true&_&ERICExtSearch_SearchValue_0=ED292376&ERICExtSearch_SearchType_0=no&accno=ED292376 An Ongoing Qualitative Study of Architecture Studio Teaching: Analyzing Teacher-Student Exchanges.]</ref>

