{{infobox observatory | name = Usuda Deep Space Center | image = The 64 m antenna at Usuda Deep Space Center.jpg | caption = The 64 meter antenna at the Usuda Deep Space Complex | organization = | code = | abbreviation = | location = | coordinates = {{coord|36|07|59|N|138|21|44|E|region:JP_type:landmark_source:kolossus-jawiki|display=inline,title}} | altitude = 1,456 m | weather = | established = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | closed = | website = http://www.isas.jaxa.jp/about/facilities/usuda.html | telescope1_name = | telescope1_type = | telescope2_name = | telescope2_type = | telescope3_name = | telescope3_type = | telescope4_name = | telescope4_type = }} '''Usuda Deep Space Center''' is a facility of the [[Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jaxa.jp/about/centers/udsc/index_e.html |title=Usuda Deep Space Center |publisher=JAXA}}</ref> It is a spacecraft tracking station opened in October, 1984. The main feature of the station is a 64-meter [[beam waveguide antenna]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Japanese deep-space station with 64-m-diameter antenna fed through beam waveguides and its mission applications |display-authors=4 |author=Hayashi, T. |author2=Nishimura, T. |author3=Takano, T. |author4=Betsudan, S.I. |author5=Koshizaka, S. |last-author-amp=yes |journal=Proceedings of the IEEE |volume=82 |number=5 |pages=646–657 |issn=0018-9219 |date=1994 |publisher=IEEE |url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpls/abs_all.jsp?arnumber=284732 |doi=10.1109/5.284732 }}</ref>
Usuda was the first deep-space antenna constructed with beam-waveguide technology. Although this construction dramatically simplifies installation and maintenance of electronics, it was previously thought to offer poor noise performance.<ref>{{cite news |title = The Evolution of Technology in the Deep Space Network: A History of the Advanced Systems Program |author = Layland, J.W. |author2 = Rauch, L.L. |last-author-amp = yes |date = 1995 |publisher = National Aeronautics and Space Administration, Jet Propulsion Laboratory, California Institute of Technology |url = http://deepspace.jpl.nasa.gov/technology/95_20/95-20.pdf |pages = 5 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110614133812/http://deepspace.jpl.nasa.gov/technology/95_20/95-20.pdf |archivedate = 2011-06-14 |df = }}</ref> However, after the U.S. [[Jet Propulsion Lab]] (JPL) tested this antenna and found the noise performance was better than its conventional 64-meter antennas,<ref>{{cite techreport |title=Use of a 2.3-GHz Traveling-Wave Maser on the Usuda 64-Meter Antenna |author=Neff, D. |journal=TDA Progress Report 42 |volume=89 |pages=34--40 |institution=JPL |url=http://tmo.jpl.nasa.gov/progress_report/42-89/89C.PDF }}</ref> it too switched to this method of construction for all subsequent antennas of their [[Deep Space Network]] (DSN).
Similar huge antennas are used by the deep space networks of the [[NASA Deep Space Network|USA]], [[Chinese Deep Space Network|China]], [[Soviet Deep Space Network|Russia]], [[ESTRACK|Europe]], and [[Indian Deep Space Network|India]].
Because the 64 meter antenna is getting old, JAXA is building a new antenna nearby. This antenna will be slightly smaller (54 meters in diameter) but have better surface accuracy and hence be capable of working at the higher Ka-band frequencies. This will increase the potential data throughput despite the smaller size.<ref>{{cite web |title=Toward a New Era of Deep Space Exploration: Kenji Numata, Project Manager, Ground Station for Deep Space Exploration and Telecommunication Project |url=http://global.jaxa.jp/article/2017/interview/vol98/ |publisher=JAXA |year=2017}}</ref>
